    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/no-comparator",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary hemolysis index validation — absolute level assessment",
      "description": "CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values were evaluated against reported experimental measurements for the FDA generic centrifugal pump. The model reproduces the rank ordering of hemolysis across all five flow-speed operating points and returns NIH magnitudes within the band described in the published literature. Uncertainty intervals derived from Monte Carlo propagation of rheological parameters (power-law exponent, consistency index) and inlet velocity profiles overlap experimental scatter at four of five points. The fifth operating point (6 L/min, 3600 rpm) shows a 22% over-prediction that the team attributes to recirculation-zone sensitivity rather than model form error. Overall, the validation activity is judged to provide adequate confidence that the CFD model captures the mechanistic drivers of hemolysis under the conditions examined. No formal comparison metric (e.g., validation comparison ratio or E_rel threshold) was pre-specified; acceptability was determined by team consensus review of graphical overlays."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/steady-flow-comparator",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Secondary hemolysis validation — steady-flow benchtop comparator",
      "description": "A secondary validation result references the Bludszuweit-Hoppe steady-flow benchtop hemolysis dataset (same pump geometry, bovine blood at 37 °C, hematocrit 35%, four overlapping operating points). The CFD model achieves a mean absolute relative error of 11.4% against this dataset, which the assessment team cites as strong corroborating evidence of model fidelity. The narrative notes that the benchtop protocol is a widely accepted reference for centrifugal pump hemolysis and that the geometric and fluid-property match is excellent. The report does not examine whether the steady-flow waveform character of the comparator experiment is appropriate for a VAD COU where the pump operates under pulsatile, cardiac-cycle-modulated inflow — a condition that alters shear-exposure history and therefore cumulative hemolysis accumulation in a manner not captured by steady-flow NIH measurements.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/benchtop-steady-flow-hemolysis-dataset",
      "validationMetric": "Mean absolute relative error = 11.4% across four steady-flow operating points",
      "comparatorNote": "Comparator is a steady-flow benchtop experiment; the declared COU requires pulsatile VAD operating conditions. Waveform character is not matched. This mismatch is not discussed in the validation narrative."
    }
